        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer87936977" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9020929826099202484">This is one of the best doorstopper HF books I&apos;ve ever read. If you like getting into a nitty gritty of politics, and people whose lives are dominated by them, this book has it all.<br/><br/>The events take place over the course of 2 short years of the war, and the tapestry Safire weaves of Washington DC in that pivotal period between Lincoln&apos;s inauguration and the Emancipation is simply amazing. Far from being impersonal or ponderous, many of the figures are very affectingly human, and their absorption i</span>
  <span id="freeText9020929826099202484" style="display:none">This is one of the best doorstopper HF books I've ever read. If you like getting into a nitty gritty of politics, and people whose lives are dominated by them, this book has it all.<br /><br />The events take place over the course of 2 short years of the war, and the tapestry Safire weaves of Washington DC in that pivotal period between Lincoln's inauguration and the Emancipation is simply amazing. Far from being impersonal or ponderous, many of the figures are very affectingly human, and their absorption into the power politics of Washington just dragged me right along with them. And for those readers who wish that HF authors would EXPLAIN their references and decisions/deviations, Safire has an immense endnotes section that I found as interesting as the main novel itself.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9020929826099202484" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
