<div id="review_611818140" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/611818140" />
    <a title="Mark Fox" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16692770-mark-fox"><img alt="Mark Fox" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1368195413p2/16692770.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/611818140?book_show_action=true">May 10, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark Fox" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark Fox" href="/user/show/16692770-mark-fox">Mark Fox</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer611818140" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17679192473360307011">The American &apos;War and Peace&apos;. A sweeping cast of characters, with military struggle as its backdrop. Freedom is great novel based closely on historical fact that achieves a fine balance between character driven narrative and military history. The account is gripping from start to finish and when the book ends, with the battle of Gettysburg, you are left wishing Safire had written another covering the remaining half of the war. It will appeal, obviously, to those interested in the civil war but r</span>
  <span id="freeText17679192473360307011" style="display:none">The American 'War and Peace'. A sweeping cast of characters, with military struggle as its backdrop. Freedom is great novel based closely on historical fact that achieves a fine balance between character driven narrative and military history. The account is gripping from start to finish and when the book ends, with the battle of Gettysburg, you are left wishing Safire had written another covering the remaining half of the war. It will appeal, obviously, to those interested in the civil war but reads well as a novel in its own right. Foxy recommends!</span>
  <a data-text-id="17679192473360307011" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
